		<hr size="1">Part 7</P><P>"No one knows what power is locked inside another; no one knows what power is locked within oneself" -- Anne Rice Queen of the Damned</P><P> </P><P>"So that's how you got these?"  Valdayana abruptly terminated the mental link she held with the ranger and indicated the objects Millikin had set out on the desk earlier. The ranger snapped back to full consciousness. She felt dizzy and did not respond immediately. Valdayana D`Varr studied the ranger intently for several minutes. Centuries of magical study had enabled the enchanter to effortlessly detect magical auras around places, people, and objects. There was clearly a magical aura surrounding the ranger that extended well beyond the typical protections the ranger employed. They did not invoke any form of magic employed by any mortal practitioner. It was also clear to the enchanter that this dweomer was linked to the ranger's life force.  She smiled inwardly at such a predictable safeguard and idly wondered if the gods had contemplated that the ranger's life would be considered an acceptable loss for the power to be gained.  But then who were they to presume to try and take what was hers by all rights?</P><P>"Ranger?" Valdayana poked the ranger.</P><P>"Yes?"</P><P>"This will not be a particularly easy or pleasant process. I can remove the ensorcelment they placed on you but I'll need a place to store the residual magics."  Valdayana neglected to mention the fact that it would entail removing the ranger's very life essence. "In fact I may need the assistance of a necromancer."</P><P>"Why?" Immediately Millikin's eyes narrowed. She suspected she knew who Valdayana already had in mind. </P><P>"I told you this will not be easy." </P><P>"I despise the very air Elegy breathes."</P><P>"As a disciple of Innoruuk, I'm sure she'd be pleased to know that she inspires such a reaction from you. Take solace in the fact that she is not particularly fond of you either."</P><P>"What could she possibly do that you cannot do yourself?"  Millikin asked suspiciously.</P><P>"I wish to take precautions to avoid any fatal accidents." Valdayana answered cautiously.</P><P>"So I have no choice in the matter?" </P><P>"Not if you want my help." </P><P>"Fine then." Millikin grudgingly conceded.</P><P>_____</P><P>"What do I owe for the privilege of your presence, Deanna?" Elegy looked up from a circle of ashes, blood, and scattered bones she had drawn around a pile of deadwood.</P><P>"I need to kill my ranger." Valdayana replied. </P><P>"So, your pale skinned plaything has outlived its usefulness. What fortunate turn of events has brought about this decision?" A twisted grin crossed Elegy's face. "Do you tire of playing mind tricks on it?</P><P>"It serves me well enough." Valdayana shrugged. "But for now, I need her death to be slow."</P><P>"You are discarding efficiency for personal desires."</P><P>"Pragmatism requires that the ranger live long enough to complete my experiment. And possibly be restored to life later should the process not work."</P><P>"A pity. Well, hopefully you will be successful in your first attempt."  The Teir`Dal necromancer's attention focused once again upon the conjuring circle she had created.</P><P>"Your free-willed cat's paw has obviously caused you a share of annoyances on its own."</P><P>"It is a fair trade off for the effort expended." Valdayana shrugged as she examined the circle more closely and noticed the slaughtered goats and chickens. "You are summoning Ghede?" The question from the enchanter was really more of a statement.</P><P>"So my time teaching you wasn't a total waste. There is much to learn from the dead."  Elegy looked pointedly back to Valdayana.</P><P>"And more still from the living."</P><P>"Yet you are here, seeking a means to glean power from death." Elegy smirked.</P><P>"True enough. What do you suggest?" </P><P>"Bleed it." Elegy responded.</P><P>"That's not practical." </P><P>"On the contrary, bleeding will give you much more control on how quickly it dies. Cut out an internal body part or sever a limb and it will die quickly."</P><P>"As I said, I may need to restore her to life. Somewhat difficult if she's missing functional organs."  Valdayana commented dryly.</P><P>"Drain the blood steadily from a single puncture or cut to a vein in its wrist or near the inner elbow. It's strength will ebb away and it will fall unconscious shortly before its life expires. It will take minutes or hours depending on the precautions to slow the bleeding. Bring me the blood you spill and I shall restore it to life should you require." Elegy spoke finally. Valdayana nodded silently. </P><P>"I know that it would despise being beholden to me for resurrecting it. And that thought gives me more satisfaction than any physical pain I could inflict upon it. How is that for irony?"</P><P>"I do believe you're developing an appreciation for mental distress."  Valdayana replied.</P><P>~~~~~</P><P>Elegy D'Varr is the sole property of her creator used for role playing purposes with prior consent. Do not duplicate.</P><P>Valdayana D'Varr is the sole property of her creator used for role playing purposes with prior consent. Do not duplicate.</P><P>Millikin Erreene is the sole property of her creator used for role playing purposes. Do not duplicate<BR><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
