		<a href="US_Show.asp?id=54087">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/profile.gif" border="0" alt="Click Here to See the Profile for Millikin Erreene" width="22" height="11"></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
		
		<a href="MB_editmsg.asp?FID=98&FN=Quellious&SID=7&SN=EverQuest&TID=2172159&TN=Closure&CAT=Servers&SURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww%2Eeverlore%2Ecom&MSID=2172709&PL=4">
		<img src="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/edit.gif" border="0" alt="Edit/Delete Message" width="18" height="13"></a>
		
		</font>
		<hr size="1">Part 8</P><P>Valdayana looked impassively at Millikin who was slumped in the chair, dead.  Elegy's prediction that the ranger's death would occur as slowly as necessary via controlled bleeding was correct.  Her blood ran in a steady trickle through a tube down to a rune engraved bowl.  She had turned a sickly white before falling unconscious.  As she bled, so too did the primal elemental energies that had been imbedded into her soul, drawn as if magnetized to a shadowy orb the enchanter had created.  At the moment of death there was a sudden surge of eldritch power as the remaining energies shifted to find purchase.  When it was complete Valdayana picked up the small orb.  Inside one could see a fire burning underwater and motes of air scattering dirt.</P><P>"Now this is a quintessence of the elements, Ranger."  Valdayana remarked, though Millikin was far beyond hearing.  She crushed the globe in her hand and felt a surge of energy race into her hand and through her body.  </P><P>"I didn't quite expect.... this."  The enchanter felt the elemental energies merging with her essense.  The searing heat of fire burned throughout only to be quenched by the chill of water, then the sudden pressure of stone weighed on her as she fell over, breathing became difficult and then she couldn't and then she was swept away by a gale.  And then Valdayana D`Varr died.</P><P>Death is not quite an accurate word though.  The elemental forces the enchanter had seized held the enchanter's spirit and kept it from dissipating.  The quintessence did not just grant permanent immortality to the enchanter but an understanding of the necessity of balance between order and chaos.  She glimpsed the forces of chaos that forever pushed and attempted to destroy the barriers that defined reality.  Balance was eroding on Norrath, and not just between the gods versus mortals but amongst the mortal population on the most fundamental levels of society.  Valdayana D`Varr willed herself back to her mortal form.</P><P>"So, that is what you were trying to tell me.  Your intellectual capacity was never as good as your perceptions though."  She poked the ranger's body.  Slowly the body began to warm as the ranger's spirit was recalled by the enchanter.  Millikin jerked forward as she returned to life and kicked over the bowl that contained her blood.</P><P>"Sorry."  Millikin frowned as Valdayana gave the ranger a look of mild annoyance.  She half knelt to pick up the bowl and saw the blood that had pooled on the floor.  Out of morbid curiosity, the wood elf ranger traced her first finger through it.</P><P>"All of this was mine?"  She blinked in surprise.</P><P>"Well it certainly isn't mine."  Valdayana answered.</P><P>"I'm surprised I didn't die from blood loss."  Millikin remarked offhandedly.</P><P>"You did die."  The enchanter responded.  </P><P>"You mean to say you killed me??!"  The ranger started in shock.</P><P>"And I brought you back."  Valdayana answered coolly.  "You said to do what was necessary."</P><P>"It was necessary to kill me?!?"</P><P>"No, I did it because I had absolutely nothing better to do with my time and thought that killing you then reviving you to let you kick your blood all over my clean floor would be an entertaining way to spend an evening."  Valdayana's sarcastic remark drew a silent glare from Millikin that the enchanter met with her own dispassionate gaze.</P><P>"Do you want to know what happened or are you going to continue sulking?"</P><P>"What?"  Millikin asked.  "Besides the fact that you killed me."</P><P>"That's a trivial detail."  Valdayana remarked.  "In any event, my process was a success and I removed the energies the gods placed in you and absorbed it into myself.  That's why I had to kill you, I could only draw it from your life essense as it was leaving the mortal plane, so to speak.  I decided to absorb it myself since it needs another sentient life force to sustain itself."</P><P>"What did you do that for?"  Millikin interrupted.  </P><P>"To increase my own power of course and find out what they were planning."  Valdayana answered before continuing.  "They intended to ensure no mortal achieves divinity without their collective agreement.  And they failed.  They're also neglecting other more important matters.  Hence why I brought you back."</P><P>"So now you're a cleric?"  Millikin scoffed.</P><P>"Were you not paying attention to anything I said to you?"  Valdayana peered intently at the wood elf.</P><P>"I'm sorry.  My attention was diverted at the point where you said you killed me."</P><P>"Verbatim, I never said that.  I said 'you did die'.  Valdayana paused before adding.  "Tell me, is that all you heard?"</P><P>"The meaning is the same."  Outwardly, Millikin remained calm but her eyes reflected a smoldering anger as she regarded the enchanter and paused to recall what was said, trying to stay composed.  "You made a comment about bringing me back and that killing me was necessary and a sarcastic remark about spilling my blood on your floor."  She paused.  "Then there was your pompous speech about absorbing the magical energies and it needing a sentient being to sustain itself."</P><P>"Pompous?  This is how you address me after I put myself at risk to help you."</P><P>"Spare me the acrimony, Valdayana.  You used my misfortune to your benefit.  As usual."</P><P>"True.  It was regrettable but necessary, Millikin.  Now as for..."  Valdayana replied and was interrupted.</P><P>"Wait.  Did you say regrettable?  Is this an apology?"  Millikin interrupted.</P><P>"I never apologize for my actions."  Valdayana looked askant at the ranger.</P><P>"But you just said it was regrettable."  Millikin countered.  "And you actually used my first name."</P><P>"May I continue?"  Valdayana inquired, deliberately ignoring the ranger's previous comment.</P><P>"Sorry.  Go ahead."  Millikin answered.</P><P>"As I was saying, the reason they granted you this boon is they want you to enter a node where an individual can alter time itself.  And you don't want to disappoint them now do you?</P><P>"What are you thinking?"  Millikin's eyes narrowed, not entirely sure she was going to like what she was about to hear.<BR><br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
	</font>
	</td>
</tr>
